From the retrieved content, I can now analyze Equation (15):

$$
\mathcal{D}_v^{(k+1)} = \mathcal{D}_v^{(k)} \oplus \mathcal{D}_{\text{retained},v}^{(k)}
$$

This equation defines how the detection set for a video $ v $ evolves from iteration $ k $ to $ k+1 $. The fusion operation $ \oplus $ is defined in Equation (16) as:

$$
\mathcal{D} \oplus \mathcal{D}' = \bigcup_{d' \in \mathcal{D}'} (\mathcal{D} \oplus d')
$$

And the per-detection fusion $ \mathcal{D} \oplus d_{\text{new}} $ is defined in Equation (17) as:

$$
\mathcal{D} \oplus d_{\text{new}} =
\begin{cases}
\mathcal{D} \cup \{d_{\text{new}}\} & \text{if } \forall d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \neg \exists(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) \\
\mathcal{D} \setminus d_{\text{exist}} \cup \mathcal{F}(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) & \text{if } \exists d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \exists(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}})
\end{cases}
$$

This means that for each new detection $ d_{\text{new}} $, if it does not overlap with any existing detection $ d_{\text{exist}} $, it is simply added to the set. If there is an overlap, the existing detection is removed and replaced with the fused result $ \mathcal{F}(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) $.

Therefore, the new retained detections are not merely added, nor are they replacing the entire set. Instead, they are being filtered and merged based on whether they overlap with existing detections. This matches option D.

