From the retrieved page image (Page 3), we can see Equation (2) and its surrounding context. The text explains that the boundary loss $ \mathcal{L}_{bound}(u) $ is defined as:

$$
\mathcal{L}_{bound}(u) = \sum_{i=1}^{N} H_i(u) \alpha_i \hat{G}_i(x) \prod_{j=1}^{i-1} (1 - \alpha_j \hat{G}_j(x))
$$

where $ H_i(u) $ is defined as:

$$
H_i(u) = 
\begin{cases} 
0, & \text{if } \phi_i = M'(u) \\
1, & \text{if } \phi_i \neq M'(u)
\end{cases}
$$

This indicates that $ H_i(u) $ acts as an indicator function that is 0 if the Gaussian $ i $ belongs to the same class as the pixel $ u $ (i.e., $ \phi_i = M'(u) $), and 1 otherwise. The purpose of this function is to penalize Gaussians that contribute to pixels of different classes, which encourages them to adjust their position, shape, or opacity to avoid crossing boundaries.

This aligns with option B: “H_i(u) penalizes Gaussians for contributing to pixels of different classes, encouraging them to adjust their position, shape, or opacity to avoid boundaries.”

<answer>B. H_i(u) penalizes Gaussians for contributing to pixels of different classes, encouraging them to adjust their position, shape, or opacity to avoid boundaries.</answer>
